The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that is comparable to the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses.
I grew up with this.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven from their bases in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government in the early 1930s.
Persecuted and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and treacherous pastoral lands, with Mao guiding the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against unimaginably bleak prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, terribly battered, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
In what extent does China's founding myth correspond to reality?
In the year 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I set out to find traces of him.
It is still a terrifying journey through areas that have changed little up to today, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I managed to locate 40 of them and conducted conversations with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or who made it to the end, but their stories were extremely revealing.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, no bigger than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and would not be released until Huang agreed.
He thought of deserting, but stayed, fearing being caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army of 86,000 had shrunk to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army on the march.
Doch starben höchstens 15.000 in der Schlacht, die übrigen verschwanden.
A different battle, at the river Dadu, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of Nationalist troops, who were guarding the Luding bridge chains with machine guns, and made the way clear for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event on the Long March, and so it is praised today as such.
Yet documents I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu first told the Party historians a completely different story. "The matter was not so complicated as people later made it out to be," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should respect the truth.
How one presents it is another matter."
So lives the legend on.
Over the Dadu, there was merely a skirmish.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, allowed Mao to pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were heading.
There were constant discussions about the ultimate goal.
When they gathered in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
Yet the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
Women were ordered to turn around and return home, because there was not enough food.
Just over a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
Yet she saved Chiang Kai-shek's abduction by the general, whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
Nor did it apply to the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's archrival, and had the task of obtaining help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
Yet Mao issued contradictory orders to them, so that they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land, where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Nevertheless, it is absent from the official historical record.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to brand her in the eyes of the Party as a traitor and to deny all the years she had dedicated to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despaired, and endured.
Hunger led the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
Executions continued until practically no officers were left to command in battle.
If the marchers had doubts, they overcame them through communist propaganda.
They endured their martyrdom with a bravery and self-sacrifice unparalleled in the history of China and other peoples.

What drove her to do that?
I interviewed one of the top generals about what he knew about communism at that time. "I had no idea then, just as I don't now," he answered. "I even doubt that Mao himself knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, a hope for a just and progressive society.
No one perhaps knew – or could have known – how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice, and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would be.
